Subject: [PATCH] PWDefault: disable hardcoded 2-cycle elimination

PathWyse's PWDefault enforces "no 2-cycles" (v→u→v) at both extension time
and at bidirectional join, on top of the ng-path relaxation. The classic
ng-relaxation (Baldacci et al. 2011) does not include 2-cycle elimination —
it permits 2-cycles when they are not blocked by the ng-neighborhood
structure.

For comparison against pure-ng solvers, this patch disables the two
2-cycle checks unconditionally. Suggested upstream version: gate behind a
new parameter (e.g. `algo/default/two_cycle_elim`) — kept simple here so
benchmarks can apply and revert it cleanly.

Reproducible difference (instance A-n80-k10-14 from spprclib, ng/set_size=8):
  unpatched: Obj = -124125 (3-cycle (75,47,65)×4, 2-cycles forbidden)
  patched:   Obj = -135733 (also exploits (78,68,78) and similar 2-cycles)

The patched value matches `bgspprc bidir --ng 8 --ng-metric cost` from the
default build (bgspprc does not implement 2-cycle elimination — it
implements the paper's pure-ng relaxation directly).

